{"raw_input_snapshot": {"task_id": "task-aa9dc2cff5", "task_type": "TEXT_SUMMARIZATION", "task_parameters": {"text": "Operational Blackbox Recorder\nComplete Development Roadmap\n\n1. Problem Statement\nModern business operations involve multiple tasks, stakeholders, and communication channels. While organizations use tools to manage tasks and communication, these systems fail to provide a clear understanding of how workflows actually unfold over time. When delays, failures, or inefficiencies occur, there is no structured way to trace back the sequence of events that led to the issue.\nExisting systems primarily focus on the current state of tasks rather than the sequence of actions that produced that state. As a result, organizations are unable to identify where exactly a process failed, who or what caused the delay, and how similar issues can be prevented in the future. This lack of operational transparency leads to reduced productivity, poor accountability, and inefficient decision-making.\n\n2. Proposed Solution\nThe proposed system introduces an event-driven approach to tracking and analyzing business operations. Instead of storing only the latest state of a task, the system records every action as a structured event. Each event contains information such as the type of action, timestamp, associated user, and relevant metadata.\nThese events are stored in a centralized event log, which serves as the foundation for reconstructing the complete lifecycle of a task. The system then organizes these events into a chronological timeline and provides a replay mechanism that allows users to visualize how the workflow progressed over time.\nBy replaying events sequentially, users can observe exactly when delays occurred, identify missing actions or dependencies, and determine the root cause of inefficiencies. This transforms the system from a simple task tracker into a debugging tool for business operations.\n\n3. MVP Development Plan (48 Hours)\nThe objective of the MVP is to demonstrate the core concept of event-driven tracking and timeline replay. The MVP should not aim for completeness but must clearly showcase the ability to record events, display them in sequence, and replay them to identify workflow issues.\nThe development begins with designing a minimal database structure consisting of two primary entities: tasks and events. The events table serves as the core component and includes fields such as event type, timestamp, user identifier, task reference, and a metadata field to store additional structured information.\nOn the backend, APIs are developed to create tasks, log events, and retrieve events associated with a task. The system should ensure that every action performed on a task results in a corresponding event entry.\nOn the frontend, a basic interface is created to display tasks and their associated events. The timeline is initially implemented as a simple ordered list of events sorted by timestamp. The replay functionality is implemented using a timed sequence, where events are revealed one after another to simulate the progression of time.\nA basic delay detection mechanism is included, where the system flags a delay if no activity occurs within a predefined time interval. This logic can be implemented using simple time difference calculations between consecutive events.\nBy the end of the 48-hour period, the system should be capable of demonstrating a complete workflow scenario, including task creation, inactivity, delay detection, and timeline replay.\n\n4. Expected Outcome of MVP\nThe MVP is expected to deliver a functional proof of concept that validates the core idea of the project. It should successfully record events, display them in chronological order, and replay them to illustrate how a task progressed over time.\nThe user should be able to observe a simulated workflow where a task experiences a delay due to inactivity or missing updates. The system should highlight this delay within the timeline, making the issue clearly visible.\nThe MVP will not include advanced analytics, refined user interface design, or complex automation features. Its purpose is to establish the foundation for further development and to demonstrate the feasibility of the proposed approach.\n\n5. Full Product Development (Next 5 Days)\nFollowing the MVP, the system is expanded into a more complete and robust product. The focus during this phase is on enhancing usability, adding analytical capabilities, and improving the overall system design.\nThe timeline visualization is upgraded from a simple list to a more structured and visually intuitive representation. Events are categorized and color-coded to distinguish between normal operations, delays, and critical issues. This improves readability and allows users to quickly identify problem areas.\nThe system introduces more advanced root cause analysis mechanisms. Instead of relying solely on time-based delay detection, it incorporates rule-based logic to identify common failure patterns such as missing dependencies, delayed responses, or incomplete actions.\nAn optional AI-based analysis layer can be integrated to generate natural language summaries of workflow issues. This feature takes the sequence of events as input and produces concise explanations of what went wrong and why.\nThe system is extended to support external data input, allowing users to upload logs in formats such as CSV or text. These logs are parsed and converted into structured events, enabling analysis of real-world workflows.\nA dashboard is introduced to provide aggregated insights, including metrics such as average task completion time, frequency of delays, and identification of bottlenecks. This transforms the system from a debugging tool into a decision-support system.\nBasic authentication is implemented to support multiple users and ensure data separation. Database optimization techniques such as indexing and proper schema design are applied to improve performance and scalability.\n\n6. Transition from MVP to Full Product\nThe transition from MVP to the full product is achieved through incremental enhancement rather than redevelopment. The existing event-driven architecture remains unchanged, as it forms the core of the system.\nThe event schema is refined to include more detailed metadata, enabling richer analysis. The frontend is redesigned to replace the basic event list with a structured timeline visualization. Additional layers of logic are introduced to support advanced analysis and insights.\nThe replay mechanism is improved to provide smoother interaction and better user experience. New features such as log uploads and dashboards are integrated into the existing system without disrupting the core functionality.\nThis approach ensures that development remains efficient while progressively increasing the system’s capabilities.\n\n7. Final Product Expectations\nAt the end of the development cycle, the system should function as a comprehensive operational debugging platform. It should be capable of recording detailed event logs, reconstructing workflows, and presenting them through an interactive timeline interface.\nUsers should be able to replay workflows, identify delays, and understand the root causes of inefficiencies. The system should provide both detailed event-level insights and high-level summaries through dashboards and analytical features.\nThe final product should demonstrate a clear and realistic workflow scenario, showing how a task progresses, where it fails, and how the system helps in diagnosing the issue. This demonstration is critical for both academic evaluation and professional presentation.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nOperational Blackbox Recorder\nComplete Development Roadmap (Point-wise)\n\n1. Problem Statement\nModern business workflows involve multiple tasks, users, and communication channels.\nExisting systems track only the current state of tasks, not the sequence of actions.\nThere is no structured way to understand:\nwhat exactly happened in a workflow\nwhen a delay or failure occurred\nwho or what caused the issue\nLack of visibility leads to:\ninefficiency\npoor accountability\ndifficulty in debugging workflows\n\n2. Proposed Solution\nIntroduce an event-driven system where:\nevery action is recorded as an event\nEach event contains:\ntype of action\ntimestamp\nassociated user\ntask reference\nmetadata\nEvents are stored in a centralized event log.\nSystem reconstructs workflows using these events.\nTimeline is generated to represent event sequence.\nReplay functionality allows step-by-step visualization.\nSystem identifies:\ndelays\nmissing actions\nbottlenecks\n\n3. MVP Development Plan (48 Hours)\nCore Goal\nDemonstrate event logging, timeline visualization, and replay functionality.\n\nBackend Development\nDesign database with:\ntasks table\nevents table\nEvents table includes:\nid\ntype\ntimestamp\nuser\ntask_id\nmetadata (JSON)\nDevelop APIs:\ncreate task\nlog event\nfetch events by task\n\nFrontend Development\nCreate basic UI to:\ndisplay tasks\ndisplay events\nImplement timeline as ordered list of events.\nImplement replay feature:\nsequential display using timers\n\nLogic Implementation\nDetect delay using:\ntime difference between events\nMark delay if inactivity exceeds threshold.\n\nExecution Timeline\nDay 1:\ndatabase setup\nbackend APIs\nbasic UI\nDay 2:\ntimeline visualization\nreplay functionality\ndemo dataset creation\n\n4. Expected MVP Outcome\nWorking backend with event storage.\nEvents displayed in chronological order.\nReplay feature functioning.\nDemonstration scenario showing:\ntask creation\ninactivity\ndelay occurrence\nNo advanced analytics or polished UI.\nFocus on validating core concept.\n\n5. Full Product Development (Next 5 Days)\nUI Enhancements\nReplace list with structured timeline visualization.\nAdd color coding:\nnormal events\ndelayed events\ncritical events\n\nAdvanced Analysis\nImplement rule-based root cause detection:\nno response\nmissing dependency\nincomplete action\n\nAI Integration (Optional)\nGenerate summaries from event sequences.\nExample output:\nexplanation of delay and cause\n\nData Input Expansion\nAllow upload of logs:\nCSV\ntext files\nConvert logs into structured events.\n\nDashboard Development\nProvide metrics such as:\naverage completion time\nnumber of delays\nbottleneck users\n\nSystem Features\nAdd authentication system.\nOptimize database:\nindexing\nefficient queries\n\n6. Transition from MVP to Full Product\nRetain event-driven architecture.\nExtend event schema with richer metadata.\nReplace basic UI with advanced timeline.\nAdd analysis layer:\ndelay detection\nbottleneck identification\nImprove replay experience.\nIntegrate additional modules:\ndashboard\nlog upload\n\n7. Final Product Expectations\nComplete event-driven system.\nFeatures include:\nevent logging\ntimeline visualization\nreplay functionality\nroot cause analysis\nbottleneck detection\noptional AI insights\nUser can:\ntrack full workflow history\nreplay events\nidentify failures clearly\nSystem demonstrates:\nreal-world workflow scenario\nclear delay detection and explanation\n\n8. Final Understanding\nThe system is not a simple task manager.\nIt is a:\nworkflow debugging tool\noperational analysis system\nBuilt using concepts from:\nevent sourcing\nprocess mining\nsystem tracing\nFocus is on:\nunderstanding failures\nimproving workflow transparency"}, "task_source_id": "runner-demo", "task_schema_version": "1.0.0"}, "guardrail_decision": {"approved": true, "required_confirmation": false}, "executor_result": "Action executed successfully", "external_timestamp": "2026-03-20T00:00:00Z"}
{"raw_input_snapshot": {"task_id": "task-d99cb0d692", "task_type": "TEXT_SUMMARIZATION", "task_parameters": {"text": "LOKESH VETTATH 8074173230 | lokeshvettath@gmail.com | linkedin.com/in/lokesh -vettath github.com/Lokesh983 | Madanapalle, Andhra Pradesh. PROFESSIONAL SUM MARY I build clean, usable web interfaces with a strong focus on interaction, clarity, and product flow. I build frontend -heavy, multi user web applications using React, integrating REST APIs and backend logic where required. I care about building real products, iterating on feedback, and improving usability rather than adding unnecessary complexity. SKILLS Frontend: HTML, CSS, TailwindCSS, React Backend : Node.js, Express.js Programming Languages: Python JavaScript UI/UX: Figma, Canva APIs & API Tools: RESTful APIs, Postman Database: MongoDB, SQL Version control: Git, GitHub Development environments: WebStorm, Visual Studio Code PROJECTS 1. Microblogging Platform React | JavaScript | REST APIs | UI/UX Design | Figma Built a multi -user web application that allows users to create posts, view a shared feed, and interact with content in a clean, responsive interface. The frontend was developed in React with a focus on component structure, state management, and smooth user interactions. Integrated REST -based backend APIs to handle user actions and data persistence, prioritizing usability, clear product flow, and real -world behavior over unnecessary features. 2. Interview Preparation Chatbot React | JavaScript | REST APIs | UI/UX Design | Figma Developed an interactive web interface that allows users to practice interview questions and receive responses through a clean, distraction -free experience. Designed user flows and screen layouts in Figma before implementing them in React, focusing on clar ity, readability, and smooth interaction. Integrated the frontend with API -based backend logic to support dynamic content, keeping the emphasis on usability and product flow rather than visual or technical complexity. 3. Gesture -Controlled Virtual Interaction System – Python, OpenCV, MediaPipe, PyAutoGUI, PyCaw Built a gesture -based interaction system that enables hands -free control of basic OS functions such as mouse movement and volume adjustment using real -time hand tracking. Utilized OpenCV and MediaPipe for reliable landmark detection from webcam input, and integrated PyAutoGUI and PyCaw for system -level control. Focused on intuitive interaction cues and responsiveness to make the user experience clear and practical rather than complex. EDUCATION Bachelor of Technology in Computer Science of Engineering, Specialized in Artificial Intelligence Aditya College of Engineering Madanapalle. | 2022 -2026 | CGPA: 8.0 ACHIEVEMENTS • Founded the VOLAR student community to create a space focused on hands -on development, collaboration, and peer learning. • Planned and executed a college -level hackathon under VOLAR, coordinating teams, timelines, and execution to deliver a high -impact problem -solving event"}, "task_source_id": "runner-demo", "task_schema_version": "1.0.0"}, "guardrail_decision": {"approved": true, "required_confirmation": false}, "executor_result": "Action executed successfully", "external_timestamp": "2026-03-20T00:00:00Z"}
